4. Kali Yuga (The Iron Age)

Duration: 432,000 Human Years
Theme: The Age of Darkness (Virtue stands on one leg)
Dominant Quality: Tamas (Inertia, Materialism)

The "Bull of Dharma" is now balancing precariously on a single leg. Truth is forgotten, and hypocrisy is mistaken for wisdom.

The Final Departure: The Shadow Falls

The Kali Yuga begins the moment Krishna departs from the earth. As he leaves his mortal body, the spirit of Kali (the demon of discord) enters the world.

The Erasure of Ritual: As rituals become corrupt and bloodthirsty, Vishnu manifests as The Buddha. He opens a new loop: the path of the Mind. He teaches that if the world is suffering, the answer lies in detachment and compassion (Ahimsa), moving the focus from the altar to the heart.

The Long Wait: We are currently in this loop. The scriptures describe a world where leaders are thieves and the climate turns hostile. We are waiting for the final closure.

The Ultimate Reset: Kalki

The Prophecy: When the darkness is absolute, a final avatar, Kalki, will appear.

The Final Loop: Riding a white horse and wielding a sword like a comet, he will destroy the remnants of the corrupt age. His arrival isn't just an end; it is the "closing of the circle."

The Rebirth: As the smoke from Kalki’s sword clears, the stars will align, and the first dawn of a new Satya Yuga will break, restarting the entire cosmic drama from silence once more.
